In college, I want to study social work. I want to work with the Division of Family and Children Services. This will help children who are abused or neglected. I will also help troubled families. My values for social work are service, respect, and commitment. These values are important for social workers and for me personally.

I wanted to help others, but I was unsure of my career path. In high school and college, I saw people ignore or cope with problems badly. I chose to study psychology. I was unsure of my career path after college. One summer, I met a boy who was escaping from abusive parents. I helped the police. This made me think about social work.

Another important value for social work is social justice. Our society says everyone is important, but we try to be like everyone else. I am an individual and I do not like to follow others. I protest against social injustice whenever I can. I will continue to do this.

This paper discusses two models of insomnia: the Biological and Sociocultural models. The Biological model looks at genetic information and medical health. The Sociocultural model studies environmental relationships and their effects on race, ethnicity, demographics, and socioeconomic status.

Insomnia is a sleep disorder. It can be a primary disorder, related to another mental disorder, or caused by medical problems or substances. Primary sleep disorders are Dyssomnias and Parasomnias. Dyssomnias include Primary Insomnia, Primary Hypersomnia, and others. Parasomnias are sleep disorders with abnormal behaviors or physiological occurrences. Other sleep disorders are related to mental disorders or medical issues.

The Biological model of sleep focuses on genes and physiological aspects. A study on mice showed that orexin neurons in the hypothalamus control sleep and wakefulness. The GABAB receptor on these neurons promotes sleep. If this receptor is blocked, it can reduce anxiety and cause sleep. Taking a drug called baclofen increases sleep time in mice. This shows that the biological model can be used in human studies. The Sociocultural model suggests that if this receptor is inherited, it can affect sleep and daily life.

This paper talks about three things about Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). First, it defines the disorder. Next, it explains how to diagnose it. Finally, it talks about how a teacher in a regular classroom can help a student with CAPD.

CAPD is when the brain cannot properly process sounds. People with CAPD can hear normally, but the part of the brain that translates sounds does not work well. This can make it hard to hear and understand speech, especially in noisy places.

The earliest talk about CAPD was in the 1950s, called "auditory imperception." Researchers started studying children with communication problems. An Italian team in 1954 started tests for these children. In 1961, a Canadian researcher called Kimura used special tests to understand the brain's workings.

CAPD can cause problems like not hearing sounds coming from different places, having trouble hearing two sounds at once, not recognizing patterns in sounds, not understanding changes in speech, and missing parts of speech. People with CAPD may also have trouble understanding the order of sounds.

To diagnose CAPD, people use different tests. These tests may include questions, observing how the person listens, and using special equipment to record sounds. There is no one test that always works, and the cause of CAPD is not known.

Teachers can help students with CAPD by:
- Speaking clearly and loudly.
- Giving visual clues to go with spoken words.
- Repeating or writing down important information.
- Using clear, simple sentences.
- Finding quiet places for the student to work.

The play Twelfth Night says, "Disguise is useful, but we must stop it to keep who we are." The problem with stopping a lie is that others might feel hurt. We must choose between protecting ourselves or keeping our friendships. Some people will not care if we lie, but others will be angry. The story of Viola in Twelfth Night is special because she pretends to be a boy. She does this to feel safe in a new place. It works, but she feels alone from other women. Olivia thinks Viola is a boy, too. This makes Viola feel confused. She also has feelings for someone who thinks she is a boy. This is hard to understand. But maybe deception shows that people have hidden feelings. For example, Olivia might like Viola as a woman, not just a boy. Olivia changes her feelings fast, from liking Cesario to liking Sebastian. This shows that Olivia might not care about the person's looks.

German colonial rule was very bad. Many people say it was very bad, especially about a group called the Ovaherero and Nama in German South West Africa. This was like one part of the whole colonial empire. German colonies were different in many ways. They had different ideas about teaching people. In German East Africa, the government helped teach people. In South West Africa, the government did not do much. They left teaching mostly to churches. The government did teach European people a lot. This had long effects on South West Africa. Many people there could not read or write. Other German colonies had more educated people. This paper wants to talk more about why this happened. It will look at the thoughts of settlers and the government. There are many books about teaching in German colonies. Most books are in German. They were written after the colonies were gone. Some books helped compare teaching in different colonies. Cohen studied teaching in South West Africa and East Africa. He said the big settlement population in South West Africa made the teaching system different. South West Africa had a nice climate, but it was still mostly desert. There were more European people there than in other colonies. By 1913, there were 15,000 European people in South West Africa, but only 5,336 in East Africa.

Popular music comes in many types. There are many genres, like rap, rock, country, jazz, and folk. Heavy metal is one of the most diverse genres. It has many sub-genres and sub-sub-genres. It began as a form of rock music with dark, intense emotions. This led to many different types, like thrash, death, and black metal. Each has its own sound and style. Heavy metal is known for its powerful guitar riffs, loud volume, and complex rhythms. It often uses lyrics about dark or violent themes. This makes it different from other pop music. The Beatles' song "Helter Skelter" is often seen as the first heavy metal song. It was made in the 1960s, influenced by a Rolling Stones song. Today, heavy metal is still evolving, with many new sub-genres and styles.

Henri Rousseau wanted to be accepted by the art world. He painted his dreams on canvas. One painting, The Dream, shows a woman in a dream. Rousseau wanted praise and recognition. He had a hard time. He had to decide if he should copy other art styles or be himself. The Dream shows this choice. Rousseau's life changed after his wife died. He worked for many years. He was older than other artists, but he wanted to be like them. He started painting in his 40s. He wanted to be famous. He was different from other artists. He copied their styles but also painted his own dreams. The Dream shows his struggle. It is a good painting from his life.

Many great thinkers say ethics and aesthetics are connected. I think they are connected because John Keats writes, "Beauty is truth, truth beauty—That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know." We learn about ethics and aesthetics through education or experience, but we often know what is good without being taught. Both ethics and aesthetics try to explain, not give rules. When we talk about a good painting or action, we often say, "There's just something about it." Art and morals cannot be fully described. They have a mysterious quality that makes them powerful. As Flannery O'Connor says, "A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way." I think this mystery is the link between ethics and aesthetics. They affect us strongly but cannot be fully explained. This is especially true for literature, as McKean says, "Morality is as important to literature as it is to life itself."

Today's Germany is strong and united. It has a mix of cultures from the mountains in Munich to the Baltic Sea city of Kiel. This culture is also felt from Cologne on the Rhine River, through the center of Germany to the Saxon city of Dresden on the Elbe River.

Germany's history comes from many different tribes. Some believe the name "Germany" came from a Germanic tribe called Tungrians, who were called Germans. Other people think it came from a spear used in battles, or an Old Irish word for "shout". The early Roman historian Tacitus wrote about the Germans in 98 AD. He said the Germans were strong and brave. He did not think they mixed with other people.

The Romans fought with the Germans. They traded goods and used German soldiers in their army. Germans lived near the Roman Empire. They traded goods and skills. They did not live in the Roman Empire.

I looked down. My mind was empty. I studied the picture, but I did not understand it. I had no thoughts. It was like I was seeing the picture for the first time. I tried to put a square around the picture to make it simple, but I could not. The bowl of fruit and the kitchen were too much. I felt small, like a beginner.

I had a book called "The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain." It taught me how to draw. I wanted to learn since I was six. The book taught me about pencils and how the brain works. One technique was to put a square around a picture. This made a simple picture from a complex one.

I tried to put a square around the bowl, but I could not. I was too impressed. I was awed by the colors and details. I wanted to draw, but I did not know where to start.

I held my brush. I wanted to create something, but the bowl was too challenging. I flushed the toilet, but it did not move. I was frustrated. I tried again, but it was stuck.

I cleaned the toilet with a mop. I studied the brown mess. I was tired. I wanted to draw, but the mess was too much. I was not sure where to start. I wanted to draw, but the mess was too much. I was not sure where to start.

Teenagers are dying on the roads. Several things make this happen. The National Institutes of Health say the teen brain is not ready for driving risks. Teenagers also have bad driving habits. They often travel with friends, which is unsafe. A study shows this.
California and other states try to make teen drivers safer. They need temporary licenses that limit when teens can drive and who can be with them. But these are only temporary fixes. The real problem is that young drivers are not ready for driving risks. A psychologist says 18 is too young for a regular driver’s license. USA Today reports that teenagers under 20 like to take risks.
Delaying driving until 19 or 20 could help. By 2010, many young drivers will be on the road. Legislation could make a big difference. Schools could teach driving, but no one under 18 could drive alone. A permit could still be given before a full license. More driving hours would be needed.
This idea is not new. It could help protect young drivers across the nation.

I look at the Library of Congress's early Edison films. I choose to watch the trick films, which are fifteen from 1895 to 1901. These films use creative editing to make tricks. My study focuses on the main tricks and some unique tricks in the later films.

Most trick films are set in one place, like in a play. The camera does not move. It uses long and medium shots, never close-ups. This is like in a theater or vaudeville show, where the audience sees the whole performance at once. Actors in trick films mostly move side-to-side, not towards or away from the camera. For example, in Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900), actors move back and forth but the camera does not follow them.

The trick films usually have one big idea per film. This makes them short, about one minute or less. They often show simple tricks like magic or switching acts, not long stories. In The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895), the whole film seems like one shot, but it is made up of many physical shots joined together to create the trick.

John Taylor was a big supporter of Republicans. He worked mainly with agriculture and had a short time in politics. These jobs showed his strong beliefs in personal freedom and government. He liked the idea of an agrarian system and thought it was the best way for people to live.

Taylor believed the United States had a good chance to create a perfect system because there were no strong traditions to follow. He thought people have natural rights and they should be separate from government. He said that the "state of nature" meant only the strong and smart could succeed, but this should not happen in society.

To make this perfect society, Taylor believed the government should consider both good and bad in people. He thought a good government should protect private property, improve agriculture, and stop capitalism. He thought a good government would work well even if it was led by people with bad intentions. He believed self-interest was normal, but it could be bad if it hurt others. A good government should watch people to keep them from doing bad things.

Taylor wanted the Constitution to be followed closely. He wanted a small government with only the powers stated in the Constitution. He thought a big government could be bad and expensive. But he also thought the Declaration of Independence was more important than the Constitution because it talked about the United States as a group of states.

Looking at Figure 17, there was a big drop in commuter log submissions in the third month. This was a little disappointing, and it is hard to know why. With winter in New England, many people do not commute by bike or on foot. December is also the end of the fall semester when people are busy with schoolwork and grades. Therefore, filling out the commuter log might not have been a priority for many. December also brings the busy holiday season with a month-long break. Classes resume in late January, which might also explain the low number of logs in February. It is possible that any commuting project has a natural decrease in excitement after the start. To fight this, we created the Carpool Challenge Week in March, which resulted in more log submissions. We also gave out many prizes to encourage alternative commuting. These prizes included gift certificates for local restaurants, coffee shops, massage therapists, and bookstores. However, it would have been interesting to see if bigger prizes, like a bike or hybrid car, would have increased participation. If we had announced these prizes in December and January, engagement might have been higher.

An ETF, or exchange-traded fund, is a security. It tracks an index, commodity, or group of assets. It's more flexible than an index fund. You can buy and sell it like a stock. ETFs have lower costs than mutual funds. You pay a commission to buy or sell ETFs. There are many ETFs to choose from. It's good to check if these benefits are real. We will look at the ETF IHF and compare it to the top 10 stocks it holds. We want to see if owning one ETF is as good as owning many stocks.

The top 10 holdings of IHF make up 63.58% of the ETF. Here are the top 10 holdings and their percentages:

To see how these stocks represent the ETF, we can calculate their Beta and return. The chart below shows these calculations:

From the chart, a portfolio of the top 10 stocks has a 6.11% higher return than the ETF. The Beta is also lower. This suggests a portfolio of these 10 stocks might do better. But, the difference between the two might not be big.

To see if the difference is big, we will calculate the standard deviation of each stock and compare it to the ETF.

Edgar Allan Poe's poem "Dream-Land" is one of his best works. He uses the word "Thule" in two lines of the poem. This word comes from Virgil's writings. Virgil used it to talk about an island north of Britain, the edge of the known world. Poe was also influenced by German writers like Goethe.

Poe liked Goethe's work. Goethe wrote a poem called "The King of Thule" in his play "Faust". In this poem, a king loses his wife and becomes very sad. He drinks a lot and decides to die. The king's story and his actions are similar to parts of "Dream-Land". Poe might have been inspired by this poem.

Poe used the word "Thule" twice in his writings. He used it as a bookend in "Dream-Land". "The King of Thule" and "Dream-Land" can be seen as related poems. In "Dream-Land", the speaker talks about a dark, lonely place. He sees dead friends and a world without color. This is similar to "The King of Thule". The speaker seems to step into the world of Goethe's poem.

Poe respected Goethe because of his work. He liked Goethe's poem "Faust". Poe also knew about Goethe's work through many copies that were made after the original publication.

Under California law, can a customer injured after slipping in a grocery store on an applesauce spill win punitive damages? If the store manager knew about the spill, but did not clean it quickly, this might happen.

A judge is unlikely to dismiss Jennifer Palmer’s punitive damage claim right away. To win, she must show that the store manager's actions were very bad and did not care about the possible harm. The store had many slip-and-fall accidents before Palmer's accident. She can argue that the manager should have known the danger of not cleaning the spill quickly.

On October 13, 2009, at 5:00 pm, an employee told the store manager, Paul Martin, about the applesauce spill. The manager was on break and said he did not have time to clean it. At 5:15 pm, another employee told the manager again, and he responded the same way. At 5:30 pm, Jennifer Palmer slipped and fell, hurting her back. Before this, five slip-and-fall incidents had happened at the store in 2009.

California law lets you get punitive damages if someone acts with “oppression, fraud, or malice.” Malice means the person intended to cause harm or did not care about the harm. Courts say conduct is malicious when a person knows the harm is likely and does not avoid it. Taylor v. Super. Ct. of Los Angeles Co., 598 P. 2d 853, 856 (Cal. 1979).

Four years ago, I took a course about Islam at CBC. We talked about if Islam is a bad religion. This question is still important today. After 9/11, news changed from being against Islam to being very nice. A president with a Muslim background, Barack Obama, could not have been possible in 2001.

The story of Muhammad, the Prophet of Islam, is interesting. I thought he forced people to become Muslims. But the story says he was a nice man who made people see the truth. He did not force anyone. People came to him on their own. This makes Muhammad seem like a special person who did not need to prove anything. This is like they are trying to take credit for Jesus' life.

The story also has many moments where people saw Muhammad's power and became Muslims. But the stories are not from directly from the people who saw Muhammad. They are told by others who told others. This makes them seem less true.

The book tries to make Muhammad seem like a godly man who is kind and wise. But history says he was not always kind. Muslims might not know the true story of how Muhammad became powerful.

Jesus' teachings and beliefs, when he lived, were not kept. Christian thought moved ahead, changing over time. Today, many people understand this history in a big way. While some people keep old beliefs, they cannot stop change. Christians will know history more in the future. They will want to know what was added to Christianity and what Jesus really wanted. It will take a long time, but the trend will change. People will remove extra beliefs, like moving a clock backward. They will follow Jesus' ideas, as if living in his time. The church will stay strong, but beliefs will become more the same. There will be less diversity. History shows change. Christians were once persecuted by the Roman Empire, but the empire became a Christian society. Our country moved from slavery to leadership. The coming change in Christianity will happen like this. People will read Jesus' words like stories, not just facts. What happened after Jesus' time?
If we look back many years, we see only Judaism, the start of Christianity. It had one god, a religion from God, and the Hebrew writings were important. The Roman Empire took Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E. The Jewish people did not agree. They had many groups: Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and many common people.

I think The Jungle shows that humans are naturally selfish. They want to make their lives better, not care for others. The Jungle shows this in many ways. The owners and managers of big factories only want to make their companies big and successful, no matter who gets hurt. They do not care about the smoke from factories or animal waste. Sinclair says, "The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world." This shows the damage the owners create. They also do not care about the workers. They want to make more money, so they force workers to work long hours and lay off many people suddenly, with no pay or help finding new jobs. There were few laws to protect workers then. The managers could treat workers badly. The workers could not escape this system. They were like slaves, "Here is a population, low-class and mostly foreign, hanging always on the verge of starvation and dependent for its opportunities of life upon the whim of men every bit as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers; under such circumstances, immorality is exactly as inevitable, and as prevalent, as it is under the system of chattel slavery."

Many writers use special words and symbols to show their ideas in a book. F. Scott Fitzgerald uses this in his novel "The Great Gatsby". He connects a word that usually does not fit with another to make an image. He also uses colors like gold, green, white/gray, and red/pink to show feelings. Fitzgerald gives these colors special meanings. He uses white/gray to show people who are the same or not important. He does this at the start of the book. People wear white clothes and white/gray cars are seen. He also uses white/gray to show unimportant people like the Italian child and the dog-seller. Then, Fitzgerald uses these colors to say that Daisy is not special. When she is in a white dress, she seems less like a character and more like something Gatsby wants. He also uses white/gray to show her fur collar and her dress before Tom and Gatsby's meeting.

San Diego County has a mild, sunny climate, perfect for growing many plants. The county grows tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, peaches, lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. People in the area like organic community supported agriculture food. Many local organizations have long waiting lists for organic food. Organic eggs and milk are also popular.

Many organic farms offer tours and recreational activities like hiking and birdwatching. This type of farming can help improve the land's biodiversity. However, organic farming is harder and more expensive than conventional farming. It needs more labor to remove pests, weeds, and fertilize the soil without chemicals. Also, organic farms may not be as efficient as large, conventional farms.

The landowner's goal is to make money and improve the land. The land is 160 acres, near the Cleveland National Forest in San Diego County, California. It is part of the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion of the San Diego Multiple Species Conservation Plan. This plan protects over a hundred plant and animal species. Many are endangered, like the Stephens' kangaroo rat, the mountain yellow-legged frog, several butterfly species, and the California gnatcatcher.

The area was once home to Native Americans, then cattle ranchers and cordwood sellers in the late 1800s. The land was used for grazing and wood production. The landowner wants to use government programs to help with costs and preserve wildlife-friendly farming. As a model, they can look at an organic farm in the same area.

Culture is important in all negotiations. Culture can be understood by what it is not and what it represents. It is not the same everywhere. Broad statements like "all Russians are stubborn" or "all Japanese are friendly" are not true. Negotiators should understand how a culture's beliefs affect talks. When meeting a foreign culture, people compare it to their own. To understand a culture, one must study its history and beliefs, not judge or try to change it. If negotiating in a foreign place, respecting traditions helps remove barriers. Culture is not just national. Companies have their own cultures. These are seen in dress, communication, and hiring. Examples include long work hours or relaxed schedules. A negotiator should learn about their opponent's personal values before talks.

The Bible says, "The fool thinks, 'There is no God.'" This idea is found in Psalm 14 and is part of St. Anselm's argument for God's existence. Thomas Aquinas also holds this belief. Since both are defending the same idea of God, we will assume they are correct. We will compare their arguments.

St. Anselm believes that God exists within our understanding. He says we don't need proof from outside ourselves. Instead, we can find God's existence by thinking about what we know to be true inside our minds. This is called faith in Christianity.

St. Thomas Aquinas, however, believes we can prove God's existence through reason and evidence. He gives five arguments: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. These arguments show that God is logically necessary.

Long ago, a prince named Buddha was born. He became wise and taught people about Buddhism. This religion is 2,500 years old. Today, it is different from when Buddha was alive. For example, in Sri Lanka, people do a water-cutting ceremony. Buddha taught about things like no soul, suffering in life, and impermanence. He also taught rules for living and four truths.

The United States and Mexico had a long rivalry for many years. This rivalry lasted from 1836 to 1893. The big fight was the Mexican-American War from 1846 to 1848. In this war, the United States won and got new land, like Texas and the American Southwest. Other fights happened between the two nations, but they stopped before the First World War.

The rivalry started because there were many disagreements. They argued about religion, culture, and tradition. They also had different ideas about how to make money. This is like what happens between other nations that share a border.

The United States and Mexico are not alone in having this kind of rivalry. Many other nations have similar problems. David M. Pletcher says that only Mexico and Cuba have long, important problems with the United States. These nations are close to the United States and have been rivals.

Religious beliefs caused a problem between the nations. Sally Frahm says that in the 18th and 19th centuries, Americans were against Catholicism and monarchy. This was like the Cold War between the United States and the Soviet Union. The rivalry was partly about political beliefs, but it was also about religious beliefs. This problem comes from the old feelings of distrust between the English and Spanish.

Diehl and Goerts list 17 problems between Mexico and the United States during their 57-year rivalry. Most of these problems were about the border. Bandits and outlaws caused many problems. Both nations had to use their army to stop this.

The rivalry ended when Mexico became more dependent on the United States. At the end of the 19th century, American goals changed from getting more land to helping Mexico's economy.

Fifteen years ago, I got sick in a way I did not know was possible. I was a nurse then. I chose this job because I wanted safety and security, which I did not have as a child. "You'll always have work, people will always get sick," was what I heard growing up.

I was 46 and single, with no money. I could not work. I am still disabled today. I live on Social Security Disability, and I have almost nothing left. Every day is hard. I need help from family and friends. Without them, I could not have survived.

Life has emergencies, big and small. Some are too big to face alone. We should not depend only on big government. We should trust and help each other. Americans should learn to ask for help, not just rely on their own strength.

Conservatives talk about rugged individualism, but our forefathers' success was due to compassion and sharing. Pioneers did not cross the Rockies alone. They worked together.

So, be ready. I have emergency supplies. But also, get to know your neighbors.

Why do organisms change over time‭? ‬Why do they change in certain ways‭? ‬D’Arcy Thompson said in 1917 that even today‭, ‬scientists have not begun to understand the simplest organic shapes in math language. But now, math is used to study mollusk skeletogenesis. We are using math and experiments to understand how Prunum species change. We used X-ray images to find numbers for modeling. We used CerioShell software to make models of shells. These models show how shells can change. We are combining these models with experiments and studies to understand big changes over time.

A shell is like a tube that turns in space. Each turn is called a whorl, which goes around a central line called the columella. The biggest whorl is the body whorl. A shell has a spire, which is all the whorls except the last. The pointy end is the apex and the other end is the base. The animal lives through an opening called the aperture.

Shells can be seen from different angles. The usual way is with the aperture facing you and the apex pointing up. A method to count whorls is shown below. First, look at the shell from the top. Then find the first line that divides the shell into two parts. Count the whorls from this line. Estimate to a quarter of a whorl.

A shell can be seen as a series of openings that move through time and space as the animal makes its shell. You can trace the path of the aperture using math and graphs. Once you have a math formula, you can change the numbers to see how the mollusk’s shell changes.

In Indonesia, the rate of death among newborns and new babies did not change much in the last ten years. The country is good at reaching some big goals, like clean water and toilet, but they do not do well with child and mother health goals. We will talk about why this happens and say that we need to fix the health system, not just make small changes. We will also talk about the problems with these goals.

In Indonesia, 72% of births now have a skilled worker, but this number includes traditional workers like midwives. They cannot help with complicated pregnancies, so many mothers die from bleeding. Also, there are fewer cases of diarrhea in children under five that are treated by a health worker. After birth, many mothers do not get good care.

Cesarean rates are still low, around 4%. In urban areas, the rate is 7%, but in rural areas, it is only 2%. This shows that healthcare is mainly available in cities, not in the countryside. Rich people also get more healthcare than poor people, so they have more money to spend on it.

To fix these problems, Indonesia must decide how to best improve healthcare services. They could make small, program-specific changes or fix the whole health system. Small changes are good because they are easy to do and show results quickly. But, there are problems with this. If we focus on one area, we might not have enough money or workers for other areas. Also, having many small programs can lead to more work and less coordination.

Victorian novels focus on detail and the aristocracy. Two books depart from this: Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights. These books use mystery and the strange to make characters stronger. They show what the characters feel and think.

In Oliver Twist, strange things happen in dreams. These dreams show what Oliver feels inside. When he thinks about the shooting, he sees it like a dream. This shows he has no control over what happens. He feels pain and fear. It is not his own fault. He does not try to stop the shooting. This shows he feels defeated. Maybe old Fagin breaks him and makes him accept this despair.

In Wuthering Heights, time passes quickly. It feels like there is no day or night. The characters feel this way too. They live in a long, dreadful silence and a short, fleeting time. They feel the same way as the day and night.

Two years ago, I worked in an after-school program tutoring elementary students. I helped them with subjects they struggled in, but I was strong in English and reading. An instructor asked me to help a boy named Adrian, a third or fourth grader, who had trouble reading. At first, it seemed strange: he spoke perfect English but had difficulty with some letters. One day, his mother visited. She didn't speak English, so we communicated in Spanish, which I was just learning. I realized Adrian could read, but he didn't know the English alphabet well. I hope Adrian is doing better now.

I share this story to talk about language barriers in schools, especially in California. It shows how hard it can be, even for children who speak perfect English. What can we do? For Adrian, tutoring in English reading helped. But for many children who barely speak English, the solution is harder. There is no one answer. We need to combine methods: dual language systems, mainstream immersion, private tutors, ESL classes.

First, dual language systems are good for all children. Children in these programs do better academically. Many people think it's a waste, but that's wrong. If we use this system in every classroom, all children can benefit. How can we do this? We don't need all teachers to be bilingual. But we can have bilingual helpers.

From the start, most people think about something big. Some learn about it in school or go to church. Others look inside themselves. Some accept the beliefs they were taught. Others do not accept them. Everyone tries to find their own way to understand spirituality. They look for light in the dark.

My father said his favorite bird is a cardinal. We sat on our porch. Rain fell on the roof. We smoked and talked. He looked thin. His hair was less. He stared at the rain. I felt alone and afraid. I hugged him. We sat together, watching the rain. I did not want to see him die. So I did not. I remembered him by how he lived, not by how he died. I lay in bed for three days, waiting for news.

No one called me.

The "Gothic Novel" is an "old-new" type of story, as Ian Watt says in "The Rise of the Gothic Novel." People have both liked and disliked the Gothic mode. Some people think it lacks real depth and others praise its "terrible sublime" effect. The first Gothic novel, "The Castle of Otranto" by Horace Walpole, mixes old and new ideas. It uses old theater and nature in a new way. The Gothic genre uses old medieval ideas, but it also creates a new form of storytelling. Even when Walpole wrote his novel, the word "gothic" could mean many things. It was seen as old-fashioned compared to modern ideas. The idea of chivalry is important in Gothic novels. It is a medieval idea, but it is used in a new way. The Gothic past is idealized and romanticized. It is used to try to make the present better. Walpole wrote his novel during a time of political trouble. He might have thought that the goodness of people in the past was lost in the present. This can be seen in his character Frederic. Frederic is a prince who has suffered and is affected by tragedy. He is also seen as a brave, courteous knight. This character shows the Gothic idea of excess.

Supply chain management is the way goods move from customer order to raw materials, then through production and distribution to the customer.

This idea was created in 1982 by Keith Oliver, a consultant. He explained how to plan, do, and control activities in the supply chain to quickly and efficiently meet customers' needs.

There are six important parts of a supply chain:
- Production
- Supply
- Inventory
- Location
- Transportation
- Information

Business managers use these six parts to give the best service to customers.

Production is the first step. It is the base for the whole process. The production stage will decide when, why, where, and how products will be made. Managers need to know what customers want. They can learn this by looking at the market. The market shows what customers need. After knowing this, managers decide what products to make and how many of them. They also decide where to make the products and which plant is best for volume and quality, keeping customers' demands and happiness in mind.

After the decision on production location, managers focus on scheduling work and keeping equipment in good condition. Production is very important. All details matter throughout the whole process. If not planned well, it could cause time and money problems in the long run.

For example, I worked at Wal-Mart and Target. Both companies have a plan, booklet, and process for everything in their business. This includes how an employee's uniform should look and how shipments from trucks should be received. Having these plans helps companies work smoothly and avoid confusion.

The second important part is supply. Supply is about making strategic decisions to choose the right facilities and outsourcing partners. A company might have many divisions for one product. Each division has different equipment, workers, and specialties. The manager decides which division is best for the different parts of the product. Management may also decide to outsource work to other companies. The main reason for this is to create velocity. Velocity is the ability to give good and flexible products while reducing costs or keeping costs low.

Hitler is alive in Burma, the sign says.

Ellen Page stands alone, a cardboard sign above her head. Burma, also known as Myanmar, is a Southeast Asian country. It is ruled by a bad group of people who came to power in 1962. They are called a "military junta." In 2007, many people protested. This is called "The Saffron Revolution." Monks, wearing robes, started the protests. At first, the government allowed them to protest. But soon, violence happened. The military attacked monks and monasteries. Many people died. One person, Kenji Nagai, was killed just for being at a protest. The government said only 13 people died. But a soldier said many more people died. This is not new. Many governments have done bad things.

The Roman emperors said they were gods and ruled everything. Japanese emperors are also said to be gods. The U.S. president talks to a man named Ted Haggard. He is the leader of a group called "Stupid People Worldwide." In 1989, people protested in Tiananmen Square. Many people died. In the 1990s, people in Rwanda were killed. In Germany, Hitler killed many people. This is called the "Third Reich."

Duke Ellington's long life and talent helped him make great music with his band. He played piano and wrote songs that showed each band member's special skills. Ellington's songs often let soloists play freely while keeping the band's sound strong and unique. He wrote pieces like Creole Love Call, where he used voice as a musical instrument. In this song, the voice and brass parts talk back and forth in different ways. His use of voice to add color in his music is one way he showed his style. In Hot and Bothered, he used "Bubber" Miley's trumpet and Baby Cox's voice to make a special sound. In It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing), he used Joe "Tricky Sam" Nanton's trombone to start the melody. Ellington's skill with sound and tone color made his music special.

She always wanted something. She did not know what. She felt this way since 14. She felt the same at 17. She wanted a person, not a thing. She did not feel interested in boys. Some boys tried to be friends, but she did not feel anything. She wondered why this happened. She thought about it for years, but she did not find answers. So, she lived her life and asked questions.

A day at home was usually calm. Her parents were good people. They did not argue. They did not argue with their daughter either. She was a happy, fun person. Her parents were calm, but she was not. She was independent and free.

Today was not calm. She heard a scream in the kitchen. She ran to her mother. Her mother was on the ground, in pain. She said, "Take me to the hospital." She carried her mother to the car and drove.

The hospital smelled of sickness. She did not feel scared because she was busy helping her mother. She carried her to the doctors. They put her on a bed and took her away. Her mother had fallen off a stool trying to get a vase.

This research showed that following a "Mediterranean Diet" (Med diet) with a high "alternate Mediterranean diet score" (aMed) lowers the risk of heart disease and stroke. The aMed diet includes more plant foods, healthy fats, and fish. It limits animal products and saturated fats. Small amounts of alcohol are allowed.

Earlier studies showed that a Med diet helps prevent heart problems and death from heart diseases. But these studies did not focus on stroke or stroke death.

This study followed 74,886 women for 20 years. They were part of the Nurses' Health Study, a group of female nurses in 11 US states. The study used food questionnaires to assess diet. It collected data six times from 1984 to 2004. Many nurses continued to participate throughout the study. The data was checked for accuracy.

The study adjusted for factors like age, smoking, weight, menopause, and exercise. It found that a higher aMed score was linked to a lower risk of heart disease and stroke. During the study, 2,391 heart disease cases, 1,763 stroke cases, and 1,077 cardiovascular deaths were found. Women in the highest aMed group had a lower risk of heart disease and stroke than those in the lowest group.

In 2007, the United States of America had a big financial problem. Many people lost their jobs, and the housing market collapsed. This problem still exists today. We want to know how this happened and how to stop it. The crisis was started by bad decisions made by politicians. They pushed banks to give loans to people who could not pay them back. Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac also helped by giving money to these loans. When the people who got the loans could not pay, the banks had no money and passed the problem to other parts of the economy.

This crisis started in the year 1999, when the president wanted to be re-elected. To be popular, he let banks give loans to people who could not pay back. Steven Holmes of the New York Times said this would cause problems. He was right.

Many things caused the crisis, including new types of loans. People used adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations. This made the economy depend on the housing market too much. When the housing bubble burst, many banks were not happy. The five biggest investment banks had $4.1 trillion in mortgage debts, which was 30% of the USA's GDP. Bear Stearns and Merrill Lynch were sold cheaply, Lehman Brothers was closed, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley became regular banks. Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac were $5 trillion in debt and were taken over by the government in 2008.

Exposition is not easy.  It is the part where you tell the audience about your story's background.  You want to share information without boring them.  Show, don't tell, is the best way to do this.

Dr. Merlin says, exposition is the little devil that tells you to share too much information.  You want to tell the audience about the past.  But you also want to show them what happens.

An example helps.  When the heroine meets her lover, you can just say they met.  But what if you show him lovingly caring for her?  Or show them sharing secrets?  Then their love is real.  When he dies, the audience will care about her more.

In short, you need to add detail and emotion.  Sometimes you want to share a character's past.  But do it in a way that shows their feelings and makes them interesting.

I watched two news broadcasts from Columbus, Ohio. The first one was live from NBC 4 this morning (August 13, 2011). The main story was about a man in Ashley, Ohio who stabbed his wife. The man's name was Shad Hostettler. They showed his photo, which looked like he was evil. They only spent two minutes on this story as it was developing.
The second story was about a shooting in the Sharon Woods area. Travis Buyers, 18, was shot and critically injured. No one was arrested. The SWAT team was investigating. This story was short. I think it might be because the victim was black, or because the neighborhood was black. I've noticed before that minorities are not given much attention when they are crime victims. If it's a white person, the media goes crazy. But if it's a minority, it's lucky if it gets mentioned.
The next story was about a bullet hole found in a Med-Flight helicopter. They said the bullet was a .22 caliber from a rifle. Crime-Stoppers offered a five-thousand dollar reward for tips. The next story was about rain and thunderstorms expected for Saturday. They said the weekend would be warm, with temperatures in the mid to low eighties. The story was short, but they wanted to use it as a teaser to keep people watching.
They also showed a story about a robbery at a Clime Road UDF in Columbus. The thief was a dark-skinned black man. They described him as wearing a hooded sweatshirt and being six feet tall, weighing about 150 pounds. They spent a lot of time describing his race and how dark he was.
Another story was about Rene Rodriguez, a convicted drug kingpin from Texas. He had been sentenced to 25 years in prison for conspiring to sell marijuana in Ohio. Instead of saying 25 years, they said "300" months. I'm not sure why they did that. They also mentioned he was Hispanic, but that didn't really fit in the story.

Brothers have a special bond; it is strong and cannot be broken. Inside this bond are many feelings: love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty. Brothers understand each other better than anyone else. They can see themselves in their brother. When a situation is bad, the true nature of this bond is shown. The feelings can cause big problems. To understand these feelings, one must deal with the results they bring. When a brother looks into the eyes of another brother, they see themselves as they really are, not as others see them. In their actions and the results of those actions, their true character is shown. In "The Scarlet Ibis," two brothers explore this theme and its strong emotions. They go on a useless journey through a beautiful, detailed landscape. In the final scene, one brother is very sad and proud, and only one brother survives. The theme is shown through the main character, Doodle, and his actions with his brother. It is also shown through the narrator's thoughts, which tell about the complex feelings of the main character and his view of the world, which greatly affect his actions.

The main character's actions are mostly caused by one emotion: pride. From the beginning of their adventures, the main character feels angry about his little brother, Doodle. He wanted a brother to teach his skills, like holding breath, running, and climbing. He wanted a brother to race with and to sit with in a tree. However, Doodle was very sick and could not do these things. The main character was very angry and even thought about killing Doodle by putting a pillow on his face. But when Doodle smiled at him, the main character's heart softened. This shows that his anger was not very strong. He truly loved his brother.

The human brain is a difficult system for processing information. As technology changed, the ways people described the brain also changed. At first, the brain was compared to a wax tablet, then to a sheet of papyrus, then to a book, and now to a computer. Remember that these comparisons can be helpful, but they can also lead to mistakes.

Information processing starts with signals from our senses, like touch, heat, sound, or light. The brain changes these signals into electrical signals. It processes these signals in two ways: bottom-up and top-down. Bottom-up processing uses simple information like color and shape to decide what we see. Top-down processing uses the decisions made during bottom-up processing to help us recognize things faster.

The brain also decides which information is important. It does this through a process called attention. For example, even though we see every blade of grass when we look at our shoes, we don't usually notice them individually. But we can hear our name in a noisy room. There are many steps in processing, and attention affects the results.

To process information, the brain must store it. There are different types of memory: sensory, working, and long-term. Sensory memory stores information for a short time. Working memory keeps information for a few seconds. Long-term memory stores information for a long time. How memories are stored is not clear. Some scientists think they might be stored in proteins.

There are many ways to organize knowledge in the brain. Some are based on how people remember things, others on computer science, and others on how the brain works physically. One way is called the semantic network. In this model, concepts are like points, and ideas are connected based on how related they are. For example, "chair" could be connected to "table" and "wooden."

Aldous Huxley in Brave New World criticizes technology and capitalism. People in this world love community more than themselves. They are taught early to love happiness. They are like players in a game, following the World Controller's rules. Looking at the book with Marxist eyes shows Huxley's worries about these systems. Marxist words like "homogeny" and "reification" show the book is a warning about the problems of the economy of Huxley's time.

Capitalism is ridiculed in the book. People do not know their true place in society because they are only interested in getting more. They are controlled by the World Controller. This is called "false consciousness". The common people, like Deltas and Gammas, have no will of their own. They are taught to spend and enjoy. The World Controller controls this. This is called "hegemony". People do not know they are being controlled. Upper classes are born knowing, but they do not do anything. Few Alpha or Beta characters like Bernard think differently. The interactions between classes show how people are controlled by capitalism.

The book has no deep relationships. Characters are all the same. Huxley may say that technology and capitalism take away people's free will and feelings. Love and strong feelings do not exist. People only talk about each other's bodies or past encounters. Each group is happy with their place in society. This shows the effects of capitalism on people's minds. They are happy as long as they follow the rules and keep up with their friends.

I have been a student here at University Park for two and a half years, or four and a half semesters. Many students, including me, have problems getting around campus. My first year, I lived in East Halls dorm, the farthest point from the center. Walking to classes could take 25 minutes, especially in bad weather. Old East Halls was once separate from the school with empty land around it. Now, that space has been filled with sports fields, new buildings, and apartments. Campus growth makes moving between places harder. What is the best solution? Bicycles. But, bicycles alone won't solve the problem. Students need to use them, and the campus must be bike-friendly.

A friend who recently started biking again said, "Bikes are great. They're the only way to get around." Bicycling is good for health and efficient for travel. A bowl of oatmeal and exercise can go 30 miles. I live off campus, far from the center. Buying a bike this year was the best decision. Walking to Thomas building daily would take 40 extra minutes. A bike cuts that time to 5 minutes. The only problem is Pollock Road, the straightest path to Thomas, is not always easy to travel. Walking is good too, but I'm too busy. Without a bike, walking would be the only option. That's over two and a half hours every week. Add other classes and appointments, and that's too much time.

Culture plays a significant role in any negotiation. Culture can be defined as much by what it is not as what it actually is and what it signifies. Culture is not homogenous, nor is it a specific thing. It is also not singular or uniform. Statements such as “all Russians are stubborn” or “all Japanese are accommodating,” are inherently broad and overly simplistic. While the understanding of a culture’s generalizations are appropriate, it is much more productive to a negotiator to understand the significance of a culture to the matter at hand, and how that culture’s attitude can and will affect the table talks. When one approaches a foreign culture, one experiences it in a way that is relatable to his own culture, and comparisons necessarily arise. 

Attempting to understand a foreign culture or mindset can involve anything from studying its history to realizing its prejudices. Rather than judging or attempting to change a culture, one must simply accept it for what it is, and work within its boundaries, especially within the scope of negotiation, and most especially if one comes to the table with a weaker bargaining position. Likewise, if a negotiator finds himself on “away” territory, a respect for traditions and beliefs can only help in getting over any cultural barriers and move the negotiation forward.

It is important to note that culture does not necessarily limit itself to a national/international dichotomy. Most companies within a given nation establish their own corporate culture. For instance, a corporate culture might emphasize long hours in the office or a more relaxed schedule. Evidence of a corporate culture can be seen in employee dress codes, in communication style (direct v. indirect communication, delegation of duties), and hiring practices. Some companies encourage philanthropy at any level from employees, others restrict it to “company approved” charities or fundraisers. One need only look at the differences in American corporate culture from company to company (and indeed, intra-company diversity exists even from region to region, urban to suburban environments included) to appreciate the diversity of thought that can reside within a particular societal culture. Certain cultures are not nearly as stratified as American culture, and may appear more uniform to an outsider, but a similar exterior is simply a sign to dig deeper. 

Values are even more important to understand, because they provide the why of a culture. If saving face or communal harmony are valued within a culture, it is certain that a negotiator will not publicly shame his company or his superior in order to succeed at the negotiation table. Likewise, a negotiator from a culture which gives greater weight to a hard-driven bargain will not necessarily be driven to settle at the earliest opportunity. Taking these generalities into consideration is important before one gets to the negotiating table. However, a negotiator is well-served to learn something about his opponent on a personal level in order to make the negotiation effective.

“The fool hath said in his heart, ‘There is no God.’” The preceding quotation is seen first in Psalm 14 of the Christian Bible, and is found at the beginning of St. Anselm’s argument regarding the existence of God. This belief seems to also be held by the other author whom we will be discussing, Thomas Aquinas. Because each of their arguments is in defense of the same concept, and our challenge is to determine who’s is the better of the two, we must, for sake of brevity, begin with the presumption that they are both correct in their belief in the existence of God, specifically the God of the Bible. To allow for a God-type figure that may not resemble the one in whom our two authors believe would not permit us to appropriately compare their two arguments, as they are essentially in defense of one specific concept of God. That being said, I would suggest that while each of them brings up valid points, neither truly provides a holistic basis for belief in God.
	To illustrate this point, we will first examine the basic argument of St. Anselm. Anselm’s passage reflects a path of gaining understanding through faith, looking within one’s self to find proof of God. He explains that because God exists within our understanding, we cannot effectively conceive his nonexistence. While this concept, when spelled out in his terminology, is a bit tedious and at times unclear, the basic gist of it is that the proof for God lies within one’s own mind. St. Anselm is suggesting to us that we needn’t go beyond the confines of our own soul to find truth about God, but that the existence of this being is found to be true simply by examining that which we inherently know to be true within our own minds. Foreign evidence is presumably unnecessary. This concept of accepting that for which there is not an irrefutable body of empirical evidence is often referred to within Christian texts as faith.
	This idea is very different from that held by St. Thomas Aquinas. Aquinas instead suggests that the existence of God can be proven entirely through reason and empirical evidence, with no need for faith of any kind. Such an idea would be beneficial in evangelism, an important element of Christianity, because it would enable the recruiting of new converts without any dependency upon their willingness to accept something that cannot be proven. They could instead be persuaded by logic alone. St. Thomas elaborates on five different logical arguments supporting the existence of God: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. In each he essentially demonstrates that the proof of God lies in the logical necessity for God. If you are told that that you are missing one puzzle piece, and assemble the rest of the puzzle, logic dictates that you can know of the features and the existence of the missing piece without having to see it.

Many authors use different ways to give their readers a certain feeling or attitude toward
important subjects. Some of these techniques are more effective than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald uses
many of these different techniques in his novel The Great Gatsby. Sometimes, Fitzgerald pairs an
adjective and a noun together that do not usually fit that way to give readers a certain aura around a
subject. Other times, he applies meaning to a symbol, and then uses it for this same purpose.
Fitzgerald uses this last technique with many colors, including gold, green, white/gray and red/pink. In
his novel The Great Gatsby F. Scott Fitzgerald builds up meaning for colors, namely white/gray and
red/pink then later uses that meaning to give readers a certain reminder of a feeling around an
important object.
The meaning Fitzgerald builds up and uses for white/gray is uniformity, with white being a bit
nicer and higher class and gray being more older and faded. Fitzgerald sets up this meaning in the
beginning of the novel with constant uses of both. Daisy and Jordan are constantly “in white” (8)—in
fact, everyone is always wearing white: Nick wears “white flannels” (41) to Gatsby’s party, Tom wears
a “white shirt” (36) when he meets Myrtle, and Catherine is “powdered milky white” (30). In fact, the
only time people are not wearing white is when Nick is getting his impressions of Gatsby’s party: “the
halls... are gaudy with primary colors” (40). Fitzgerald further defines these two colors in coloring
many common, unimportant subjects these colors: as Nick goes to work, he goes “down the white
chasms of lower New York” (56), the names of people at Gatsby’s parties are now “gray names” (61)
on Nick’s timetable, Catherine’s apartment is “one slice in a long white cake of apartment-houses”—
uniformity (28). He also describes plain or common people or places as white or gray: Jordan and
Daisy had a “white girlhood” (19) together, there are “gray cars” and “gray land” (23) in the valley of
ashes, the “Italian child” in the railroad is “gray” (26), and the dog-seller is “a gray old man” (27).
After Fitzgerald adds enough meaning to white/gray, he uses them to signify unimportance or
uniformity to certain subjects. This using colors to show readers something first starts with Daisy.
After a long time without any significant use of either of these colors, Fitzgerald comes out describing
Daisy as “dressed in white” in “a little white roadster”; readers begin to see Daisy as less of a character,
more like just a uniform addition, something that Gatsby wants and longs for (74). Fitzgerald uses
more of this technique around Daisy to give this impression of Daisy being a more uniform addition,
for example, there is a “gray haze of Daisy’s fur collar” (18), and she is again in a “white” (115) dress
before Tom and Gatsby’s encounter.

San Diego County is very agriculturally productive, thanks to a mild, sunny climate. Common crops include: tomatoes, citrus, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, tree fruits like peaches and lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. There is a substantial market for organic community supported agriculture food in the San Diego area, with many local organizations having lengthy waiting lists. Organic eggs and milk are also popular. Many organic farms also provide tours of their agricultural operations as well as access for hiking, birdwatching, and other recreational activities. This is the type of operation that would allow the landowner to gain the benefits of government programs while improving habitat, thus allowing recreational use and creating an opportunity for farm tours and other programs for making money or for educational purposes.  
	In addition to filling a potentially lucrative niche market, the benefits of organic farming often include greater biodiversity in plants and wildlife in the area thanks to a lack of chemicals in the soil and water. However, organic farming has greater costs than conventional farming in some ways. It requires more intensive labor and management to remove pests and weeds and fertilize the soil without chemicals, and losses are often greater than with conventional methods, while a small organic farm also lacks the efficiency of scale of large operations. Practices not related to organic farming but beneficial to wildlife may also incur greater labor costs, including planting cover crops, strategic grazing rotation, invasive species removal, and active management of plant growth to provide specific conditions such as edge habitat or patches of open ground. Thus, there are many reasons why the landowner in this example might seek financial help or expertise in maximizing both profits and habitat quality.  
The land chosen for this scenario is a parcel adjacent to the town of Potrero, in unincorporated San Diego County, California. It is 160 acres of chaparral, nonnative Mediterranean grassland, and oak woodland next to to the Cleveland National Forest. It lies in the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion of the San Diego Multiple Species Conservation Plan. The plan is still being reviewed, but presently considers over a hundred species of plants and animals. Many are endangered, such as the Stephens' kangaroo rat, the mountain yellow-legged frog, several species of butterfly, and the California gnatcatcher; others are declining and may soon be listed, such as burrowing owls.
	This area was inhabited by Native Americans for untold centuries and was then settled by cattle ranchers and cordwood sellers in the late 1800's. This piece of land was part of an original homestead patent and so was probably used for grazing and/or wood production for many of the intervening decades.
	 chose a piece of property from a real estate website and researched available government programs to see what options a small farmer might realistically have for mitigating costs and preserving wildlife-friendly operations.  As a model of what somebody farming this land might attempt to achieve, I located an organic farm in the same area.

There is a bond between brothers; an unbreakable, irrevocable bond. Within that bond lie many emotions: love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty, just to name a few. Brothers understand one another, far more than anyone else with that kind of bond, and they can only see themselves when looking at their brother. It is when a situation is at its most dire when the true nature of this bond shines through, be it good or evil. When these emotions become clear, they carry with them great a cost. Part of understanding the emotions born of this fraternal link is dealing with the consequences that they bring. When one can look a brother in the eye and see within that person their own reflection, they see themselves not as others see them, but as they truly are. In their actions and the consequences of those actions is where their true character lies.  In “The Scarlet Ibis”, two brothers explore this theme, and all of the raging emotions that accompany it. Throughout a lush, vividly described landscape, these two boys set out on a futile journey. Bitter disappointment clashes with intense pride in the climactic scene, and only one brother escapes with his life. The theme is expressed through direct characterization of the protagonist, Doodle, and their interactions with each other, as well as through the narrator’s point of view, which communicates the complex feelings experienced by the protagonist and his view of the world around him, both of which are heavy influences on his actions.
	The protagonist’s actions can all be summed up by one key emotion: pride. From the time he and his little brother, Doodle, first go out together, to their final, fateful excursion, the protagonist feels resentment towards Doodle. He had wanted a brother whom he could teach all of his worldly skills, like “…holding my breath, running, jumping, or climbing the vines in Old Woman Swamp…” He wanted a brother who could fill the role of “…someone to race to Horsehead Landing…and someone to perch with in the top fork of the great pine behind the barn…” Obviously these things are impossible, given Doodle’s condition. Doodle was born with an extremely weak heart, making in unlikely he would even survive. Even then, it was nearly impossible that he would ever participate in vigorous physical activity. What a blow to the young protagonist, his head filled with wild fantasies, to have all of those dreams crushed in an instant. In fact, he is even shown to bear some anger towards the small child, as he recalls beginning to contemplate killing him by suffocating him with a pillow. What kind of child would have the presence of mind to consider infanticide? However, his heart melts when the small child smiles at him. Such a simple act gave the protagonist such hope! This shows that his conviction probably was not very strong. In the back of his mind, he had an instinctive love for his brother.

The human brain is a complicated, creative information-processing system. As technology advanced from primitive to modern, the metaphors used to describe the brain also advanced. Initially, it was compared to a wax tablet, then to a sheet of papyrus, then to a book, and most recently, to a computer. As you learn about the brain, keep in mind that the usefulness of these metaphors is limited and can lead to erroneous conclusions.
Information processing starts with input from the sensory organs, which transform physical stimuli such as touch, heat, sound waves, or photons of light into electrochemical signals. The sensory information is repeatedly transformed by the algorithms of the brain in both bottom-up and top-down processing. For example, when looking at a picture of a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing puts together very simple information such as color, orientation, and where the borders of the object are – where the color changes significantly over a short space – to decide that you are seeing a box. Top-down processing uses the decisions made at some steps of the bottom-up process to speed up your recognition of the box. Top-down processing in this example might help you identify the object as a black box rather than a box-shaped hole in the white background.
Once information is processed to a degree, an attention filter decides how important the signal is and which cognitive processes it should be made available to. For example, although your brain processes every blade of grass when you look down at your shoes, a healthy attention filter prevents you from noticing them individually. In contrast, you might pick out your name, even when spoken in a noisy room. There are many stages of processing, and the results of processing are modulated by attention repeatedly.
In order for the brain to process information, it must first be stored. There are multiple types of memory, including sensory, working, and long-term. First, information is encoded. There are types of encoding specific to each type of sensory stimuli. For example, verbal input can be encoded structurally, referring to what the printed word looks like, phonemically, referring to what the word sounds like, or semantically, referring to what the word means. Once information is stored, it must be maintained. Some animal studies suggest that working memory, which stores information for roughly 20 seconds, is maintained by an electrical signal looping through a particular series of neurons for a short period of time. Information in long-term memory is hypothesized to be maintained in the structure of certain types of proteins.
There are numerous models of how the knowledge is organized in the brain, some based on the way human subjects retrieve memories, others based on computer science, and others based on neurophysiology. The semantic network model states that there are nodes representing concepts, and that the nodes are linked based on their relatedness. For example, in a semantic network, “chair” might be linked to “table,” which can be linked to “wooden,” and so forth.

In 2007, the United States of America fell into a crushing financial crisis. Unemployment increased, the housing market crashed, and many of America’s largest and most important corportations were left in ruin. This recession persists today, so we must ask the question: how did this crisis occur, and how can we stop it? In short, the financial crisis was created by selfish and naïve political decision-making that pressured banks and firms into issuing sub-prime loans into an already immature and unsufficient financial infrastructure. Meanwhile, Fannie Mae (FNMA) and Freddie Mac (FHLMC) were pressured to underwite and repackage these mortgages into CDO’s and CDS’. When borrowers defaulted on these loans, the banks were short on capital reserve and transferred this chaos onto the repacked mortgages that they had sold, and on to the rest of the economy.
	The financial crisis had its roots in 1999 of the Clinton era, as the President was aiming for a second term in office. He sought to extend his presidential tenure by augmenting his popularity. To accomplish this the Clinton administration relaxed lending restrictions, which helped to set the grim stage for the sub-prime crisis seven years later.  Steven Holmes of the New York Times reported in 1999, “Fannie Mae, the nation's biggest underwriter of home mortgages, has been under increasing pressure from the Clinton Administration to expand mortgage loans among low and moderate income people and felt pressure from stock holders to maintain its phenomenal growth in profits.” Holmes would go on to correctly foresee the consequences of these actions: “But the government-subsidized corporation may run into trouble in an economic downturn, prompting a government rescue similar to that of the savings and loan industry in the 1980s.” As detailed in the introduction, and as Holmes foresaw, ill-advised lending would certainly lead to the meltdown of the economy.
	Many factors combined to throw the economy into tailspin, one of which was the new and complex structure of mortgages. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDO’s) were all used extensively in the years leading up to the crisis, and only served to intertwine more sectors of the economy into the housing market. This led to U.S. households, and financial markets in general, to overleverage themselves in the housing market, leaving them extremely vulnerable to even small changes in price. 
	Indeed, the housing bubble burst, and the financial institutions that had bought these mortgage-backed securities were spited. The top five U.S. investment banks all together reported $4.1 trillion dollars of mortgage debts in 2007, which accounted for about 30% of the USA’s GDP. In the end, Bear Sterns and Merrill Lynch were sold exceptionally cheap, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were forced to become commercial banks subjected to intense regulation. Fannie and Freddie were $5 trillion in mortgage debt, and were placed under government control in September 2008.

Ah, exposition.  That place in your story where you stretch your little writer's wings and take flight, astounding one and all with your magnetic, nay magical prose.  Or the part where your readers fall asleep and/or hit the "Back" button while cursing your name.  Dr. Merlin has been known to shout at her monitor when she finds herself in the middle of Too Much Information, and not even in the fun way.

Exposition is not your friend.

My gentle readers already know the basic writing tip, "Show, don't tell," but Dr. Merlin still stumbles into long passages of text where nothing happens, or worse, too much.  Exposition is the little devil sitting on your shoulder that says to get the history out of the way to get to the good parts (not to be confused with the devil sitting on the other shoulder urging the author to tell her audience every single detail of the childhoods of each character).

Exposition means telling the audience what happened, typically in simple prose.  In film, the exposition happens when one character tells another a core-dump of information ala "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner."  In fiction, the author's doing the telling.

An example is in order.  As you are reading a story, you are told that the heroine met her beloved at such a place and time, that they were married in a gala fashion, and that her husband was murdered in front of her eyes.  You would not expect this entire sequence to take two pages, during which time both he and she only get two lines of dialogue each.  You would expect the author to spend some time on the husband's character, evidencing by his speech and manner how deeply he loves his wife, and you would equally expect the heroine to show through big and small ways how much his presence in her life changed and enriched her (especially if the story were to tell you flat out later that this was the case).  A proper introduction to the husband's character would allow you to become emotionally involved with his fate and would give you insight into the heroine's character: what she saw in him, how deep their bond was, clues about her thoughts and beliefs and dreams as reflected through the prism of his eyes, and so on.  You would mourn his death with her, and so grow more connected to the heroine herself.

In short, you would expect meat on the simple bone of the storyline: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, you need to provide that meat.  (*looks at metaphor, sighs, plunges onward*)  Sometimes it is tempting to rush past certain things.  Perhaps you're introducing a new character and you know he used to be in the Air Force, and he's the night manager of a gas station now, and he was married twice, no kids, likes to go fishing on the weekends, secretly dreams of owning the gas station someday and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.
